    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-11-26T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-11-26T06:00:00-05:00" n="193"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d193">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">641.74/11–2651: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Egypt</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_CJ1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d193fn1">Repeated to London, Paris for <persName
                            corresp="#p_MDII1">MacArthur</persName>, Rome for <persName
                            corresp="#p_ADG1">Acheson</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-11-26T13:00:00+02:00"
                            >November 26, 1951—1 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>767. <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 801 Nov 23.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d193fn2">Not printed.</note> “Necessity giving Brit troops rest”
                    formula is not to be taken seriously.</p>
                <p>I agree that immed shut-off effects will not be disastrous. Brit generals are
                    having tough time and we shld be indulgent (<gloss target="#t_Deptel1"
                        >Deptel</gloss> 807 <pb facs="0467" n="427" xml:id="pg_427"/> Nov 25).<note
                        n="3" xml:id="d193fn3">Not printed.</note> I suggest that we let them play
                    their game for next 2 weeks altho it is bound to have adverse effect on my
                    Serageddin convs and of course King will be particularly angry.</p>
                <p>However, if this state of affairs is allowed to continue “as is” Egypt will
                    eventually fall into lap of my Russian colleague like an overripe plum. Only
                    thing that stands in way of this is our still considerable prestige. Therefore
                    if Brit mil are still playing their game at end of fortnight I reluctantly
                    suggest that there is only one way left for us to protect ourselves and that is
                    the next time after the fortnight they turn off the tap Dept spokesman answer in
                    reply to a planted press question that the US has no responsibility in case of
                    the Brit mil shutting off fuel supplies from Egypt.<note n="4" xml:id="d193fn4"
                        >In telegram 847 to Cairo of November 30, <persName corresp="#p_WJE1"
                            >Webb</persName> informed <persName corresp="#p_CJ1">Caffery</persName>
                        that as a result of <persName corresp="#p_ADG1">Acheson</persName>’s
                        intervention with <persName corresp="#p_DA1">Eden</persName> on the oil
                        cutoff issue, as reported in telegram <gloss target="#t_Secto1"
                            >Secto</gloss> 87 from Rome, <hi rend="italic">infra</hi>, “it will not
                        be necessary consider suggestion re press statement US non-responsibility re
                        oil shutdown.” (641.74/11–2951)</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
